<TEXT>
dont bulldoze the berlin wall just yet says 
a california businessman who wants to buy it and sell chunks for 
souvenirs 
barry stuppler a precious metals and coins dealer said 
saturday he tried to offer the east german government 50 million 
for the wall after watching tv reports of berliners ripping out 
chunks as keepsakes of the day the communist government ended 
travel restrictions 
to be candid with you i think i could merchandise it said 
stuppler president of gold and silver financial group 
stuppler said he hopes to put together an investment partnership 
of about 50 people to quickly raise funds to buy salvage rights 
they the east germans need hard currency and i have an 
interest in spending the money and doing it he said what else 
are they going to do with it the wall anyway 
stuppler said he had called the east german embassy in 
washington dc and was told someone would get back to him next 
week 
an embassy employee who refused to give his name said he hadnt 
heard of stupplers bid but added that the people who would handle 
such a proposal were out of the office for the weekend 
stuppler acknowledged hes unlikely to get title to the wall 
which is already being picked at by souvenir hunters after looming 
for 28 years as a grim symbol of the division of east and west 
berlin 
if he were to succeed he would cut the wall into small chunks 
for sale with each keepsake piece certified as authentic by the 
east german government 
i think direct sale of it would probably be very easy he 
said i think this is a piece of history well worth saving for 
posterity 
