<DOCNO> AP891112-0013 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
colleges run by indian tribes have inadequate 
salaries and libraries and often operate out of trailers because of 
eroding federal support according to new study released sunday 
us support for the 24 colleges serving some 4400 indian 
students has been woefully insufficient concluded tribal 
colleges shaping the future of native americans by the carnegie 
foundation for the advancement of teaching 
their accomplishments have occurred despite the federal 
governments benign neglect and a lack of national awareness of 
their merits said the 103page report 
the first and largest navajo community college in tsaile 
ariz was founded in 1968 and has more than 1000 students 
twentythree others have opened in montana arizona north 
dakota south dakota california oregon nebraska minnesota 
wisconsin and illinois most are twoyear colleges 
approximately 90000 indians attend us colleges according to 
federal statistics and nearly all attend nonindian institutions 
many such schools have become more hospitable to indians and at 
least 85 have established indian studies programs according to the 
carnegie study 
nonetheless mainstream colleges have a poor record with such 
students almost 90 percent drop out the report said 
unlike past programs that frequently encouraged indians to deny 
their heritage a central mission of tribal colleges has been to 
help tribes reclaim their cultural heritage wrote foundation 
president ernest l boyer in a foreword to the study 
eleven years ago congress authorized the government to provide 
4000 for each fulltime student at tribal colleges and a lesser 
amount for parttime students the authorized grant per student was 
later increased to 5825 but actual appropriations never 
approached those figures the report by the princeton njbased 
foundation said 
in 1980 when there were only about 1700 students in tribal 
colleges the federal government distributed 5 million under the 
tribally controlled community college act about 3000 per 
student the report said 
by 1989 with enrollments up nearly threefold the 
appropriation climbed to 85 million but the amount generated for 
each student declined to 1900 in effect tribal colleges are 
being penalized for their own success said the report 
federal funding up to authorized levels headed the list of 10 
recommendations in the report which also called for increased 
support from states and private foundations 
many tribal colleges are forced to carry on their work in 
trailers and abandoned government buildings that other colleges 
would have hauled away or bulldozed over 20 years ago it said 
such poor facilities not only restrict learning but also make 
a powerful statement of neglect said the study 
the report the first to examine the work of tribal colleges 
was written by paul boyer a journalism instructor at california 
state university at sacramento and comes at a time of heightened 
attention to the plight of indian education 
two foundations the macarthur foundation and us west were 
scheduled to announce multimilliondollar grants to aid tribal 
colleges and other indian institutions at a news conference in 
washington on monday 
last month us education secretary lauro f cavazos announced 
plans for an indepth study of indian education the joint study by 
the education and interior departments will review the 
effectiveness of government programs affecting indian education he 
said 
tribally controlled colleges were spawned in the midst of the 
1960s civil rights era when indians and other minority groups were 
actively rejecting assimilationist arguments and demanding a voice 
in running institutions affecting them 
since their beginnings many tribal colleges have offered 
tutoring in basic skills and extensive counseling at some faculty 
and administrators visit the homes of students who start missing 
classes 
tribal colleges offer social and economic services to entire 
indian communities many offer adult education or work with local 
businesses to enhance the local economy 
typical students are older than the average college student 
female and living on reservations at fort berthold college in 
north dakota for example the average student is 33 many come to 
tribal colleges failing at traditional colleges 
college presidents are nearly all indians and all colleges are 
chartered and controlled by tribal advisory and governing boards 
but most faculty are nonindian and low pay and isolation have 
led to a high turnover rate the report found 
twelve are fully accredited and eight are candidates for 
accreditation according to the report 
clearly tribal colleges are not marginal institutions that 
have been given a break it said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
copies of the report are available for 8 from 
princeton university press 3175 princeton pike lawrenceville 
nj 08648 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

