<TEXT>
ashland oil inc has agreed to pay the state 
4 million for damage caused by the oil companys massive diesel 
fuel spill south of pittsburgh last year according to a published 
report 
the agreement not yet public was expected to end extensive 
negotiations between ashland based in ashland ky and the 
pennsylvania department of environmental resources the pittsburgh 
press reported in sunday editions 
the payment would be for alleged violations of state 
environmental laws and damage to drinking water fish waterfowl 
and other resources in connection with the spill which occurred 
jan 2 1988 at ashlands floreffe terminal in jefferson 
more than 700000 gallons of diesel fuel flowed into the 
monongahela and ohio rivers when a storage tank ruptured 
the spill killed thousands of fish and birds and forced public 
water systems in three states to stop drawing from the the rivers 
charles duritsa a state environmental official involved in the 
negotiations confirmed the 4 million figure 
ashland also has agreed to reimburse pennsylvania agencies for 
overtime expenses equipment purchases and other costs stemming 
from the spill under a separate settlement reached several weeks 
ago but not yet made public the press said 
officials told the newspaper that sum would be in the sixfigure 
range but they would not be more specific 
the settlement would bring to about 4325 million the amount 
ashland has spent or commited itself to spend on spillrelated 
damage and expense claims by individuals businesses and government 
agencies on civil penalties for a criminal fine for settlement 
of a classaction suit and for the cleanup 
the figure consists of about 14 million for damages expenses 
and civil penalties including the 4 million pennsylvania 
agreement 11 million for cleanup 225 million for a criminal 
fine and up to 16 million under the terms of a classaction 
settlement filed in us district court in pittsburgh last week 
the costs have not have a significant impact on the companys 
earnings according to ashland spokesman robert schrum ashland had 
to pay a 25 million deductible but insurance comvered the 
balance of the damage and cleanup costs he said 
</TEXT>
